<br>
The vast majority of the time, starvation in poor countries is due either to natural disasters unpreventable by anyone, which they are not prepared to handle, or poor management of available resources, often due to political instability and conflict, or more often a combination of the two.  Hayzen seems to believe that there are areas in the world where the size of the population has, or soon will, outstrip its ability to support itself - such Malthusian doomsday scenarios have repeatedly, consistently, been proven false.  Agricultural technology &amp; ability has been able to more than keep up with rising population - the problems have been elsewhere.  People in Ethiopia and Somalia may have been starving, and there may have been droughts or famines, but if there had been a competent, even minimally efficient government in place, there wouldn't have been nearly the problem there was.  Therefore giving these people food isn't enabling them re: reproduction, however as in Somalia, it is certainly possible to stick our noses into something we aren't prepared for or fully understand and either accomplish nothing beyond the short-term (people fed for a few months, after which they starve again), or even making the situation worse through our own ignorance or mismanagement of do-gooding (disrupting the balance of power between warlords, etc.).  The real problem is often something that only the people of the nation in question can really solve - or we can try, like we are in Iraq, but not many nations are willing to take that sort of responsibility very often, for good reason. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caledhontelrana>Caledhon TelRana</A> at: 9/17/03 8:35 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20"