<td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: We have no obligation to the world's needy.</span><hr size=1> &quot;But wise sovereigns seem not to exist in the poor world today. The most anguishing problems are created by poor countries that are governed by rulers insufficiently wise and powerful.&quot;<br>
<br>
Baloney, wise sovereigns (comparatively, or at least wise enough not to starve their people) exist in the &quot;poor world&quot;, but they don't get attention because there's no significant problem, certainly not regarding starvation etc.  The entire continent of Africa isn't starving.  Where you have a Somalia, or an Ethiopia-Eritrea, or any Mugabe-ized nation, you'll have trouble.  Giving these people food, like I said, is always a problematic solution, but to dismiss it categorically is silly - such situations are always complex, and if a nation feels that interference is within its national interest (which is increasingly global), then it would do well to examine the situation and determine what the best course of action is, given the amount of resources it is willing to spend in an effort to assist that country.  If that amount is small, it may elect only to ship over some food for short-term aid.  If that amount is large, it may elect to do something else.  There is always the chance of good intentions going awry, which is essentially what Hayzen argues, but he makes it sound as if this is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>always</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the case, and he puts it in terms of reproduction, which is silly.  So what, you expect a nation experiencing political trouble to stop having sex suddenly so there are less mouths to feed?  No, that's not what happens, and never has been.  The analogy is bad.  When we give food to nations under corrupt, evil regimes such as, for example, Iraq, what we're enabling are not the rabbit-like reproduction impulses of the populace, but the repression and evil of the regime.  This is a strong moral dilemma, of course, and one which is not easily resolved.  The food helps the people, but it allows the Husseins of the world to maintain power and spend more money &amp; effort on other things than feeding his population.  The solution is not always obvious...<br>
<br>
As for the population decline/increase thing, I'm not impressed or bothered.  The &quot;underdeveloped world&quot; is unlikely to remain that way forever, and that's part of what the &quot;developed world&quot; has been trying to accomplish with its assistance.  You seem to propose a binary choice: the underdeveloped world either is enabled and balloons to frightening, unmanageable size, or it is abandoned to its fate of growth/starvation cycles.  Isn't it more likely that something in between will turn out, as the underdeveloped world slowly develops?  So we may wind up with a billion more people in Africa - if they can be fed, so what?<br>
<br>
Oh, and the World Food Bank is a load of socialist BS.  Considering that it's sole mission seems to be simply feeding people, I would definitely say that it's a little on the scary side.  While feeding starving people may seem to be a good moral decision, like I have said, situations are often much more complex than that.  It'll be funny when they go in and feed up a few million people who suddenly decide it's going to be a good idea to go mow down a few million of the tribe across the river, who are still too weak &amp; starving to defend themselves (just as a random silly example...). <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caledhontelrana>Caledhon TelRana</A> at: 9/17/03 9:19 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hayzen>Hayzen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I read boards more<br>than I play EQ....</span><br>  Posts: 779<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(9/17/03 9:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=876.topic&index=36>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~digitalfoenix/nicholaswolfwood.JPG height=44 width=64></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: We have no obligation to the world's needy.</span><hr size=1> Wolvar,<br>
